				Rob, thanks.  The Wiki page is exactly what I needed to find.  I agree that this erases my key premise and I have adjusted the post (and will make a follow-up).<BR/><BR/>Yes, on provisional and exploratory implementations, with the usual caveats and concerns about releasing these into the wild before the specification is fully-baked at some level.<BR/><BR/>I think the .htm and .html situation is murkier, and for those of us who don't build web servers or browsers, mainly resolved by MIME type text/html in HTTP response headers.  This very blog page, with URL ending in .asp, is actually served up as tet/html, for example (long story).  Also, the magic numbers and MIME types for ODF packages should be sufficient.  I need to try that out with some ODF-supporting applications.<br />
